<tr><td><font color="#EE0000">**************************************************************************</font></td></tr>
<tr>
  <td height="31">ZincBinder: Svm based approach for predicting zinc metal binding sites in protein sequences</td></tr>  	
<tr>
  <td height="28" >Developed By: Abhishikha Srivastava,Manish Kumar</td></tr>
<tr><td >Department of Biophysics,University of Delhi South Campus Newdelhi, India</br></td></tr>			                                                     
<tr><td > <font color="#EE0000">************************************************************************** </font></td></tr>
<tr><td align=""><font color="#990033">About ZincBinder</font></td></tr>
<tr><td>=============</td></tr>
<tr>
  <td align="justify">Zinc metal ions play structural, signaling and regulatory roles  in many biological systems
    that includes stablization of membranes and various transcription factors and also the catalytic activity of various enzymes. We have developed a method &quot;<font color="#CC6600">Zincbinder</font>&quot; for predicting  zinc metal binding site from their amino acid sequence. We have developed SVM  models using 
    PSSM and achieved maximum accuracy 86.2% respectively. Its webversion is available from <font color="#0000FF">http://proteininformatics.org/mkumar/znbinder/</font></td></tr>
<tr>
  <td><font color="#990033">Availability and requirement</font></td></tr>
<tr><td>======================</td></tr>
<tr><td align="justify"><p>ZincBinder is written in PERL language, in order to run Zincbinder one need to 
  have or install PERL (http://www.perl.com/). It is a SVM based program 
  where models have been developed using SVM_light.Thus user should have 
  or install svm_classify of SVM_light from
  http://www.cs.cornell.edu/People/tj/svm_light/.</p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <p>Operating system(s): Plateform Independent</p>
    <p> Programming language :perl</p>
    <p>Other requirements: gcc++ compiler</p>
    <p>License: GNU GPL</p>
    <p>Any restrictions to use by non-academics: none</p>
   </td></tr>
<tr><td><font color="#990033">Downloand and Installation</font></td></tr>
<tr><td>==========================</td></tr>
<tr><td><p>1. Download <a href="znbinder_standalone.tar.gz">znbinder_standalone.tar.gz</a></p>
    <p> 2. Unzip using command: gunzip       znbinder_standalone.tar.gz</p>
    <p>3. Extract files: tar -xvzf znbinder_standalone.tar      </p>
    <p>4. Change directory: cd standlone</p>
    <p> 5. Run program : perl znbinder.pl      </p></td></tr>
    <tr><td><font color="#990033">How to Use</font></td></tr>
    <tr><td>==========</td></tr>
    <tr><td><p>1. Run using "znbinder.pl" or "./znbinder.pl" or "perl znbinder.pl"</p>
	<p>2. Usage: znbinder.pl -i [input_file] -t [threshold]</p></td></tr>
    <tr><td><p>Options:</p>
	<p>-i    	    Input_file containing sequence(s) in the FASTA format. </p>
	<p> -t   	    SVM threshold (from -1.00 to 1.00; default 0.1)</p></td></tr>
    <tr><td><font color="#990033">Files and Directory</font></td></tr>
    <tr><td>==================</td></tr>
    <tr><td><p>README                  description file 
	   helps to understand and use  all the related program
	  in zincbinder             directory having SVM models with main program zincbinder.pl .
      </p></td></tr>
    <tr><td><font color="#990033">Example Usage</font></td></tr>
    <tr>
      <td>perl zincbinder.pl -i seq.fasta  -t 0.0</td></tr>
    
  </table>
  
